      "span_text": "We agree with Schlenker in his response to Rainey and Schonfeld  that, in low-prevalence populations, positive results, true and false alike, will be few and, therefore, in a practical public health context, where the concern is to minimize contamination errors, it is more meaningful to report false positives as a fraction of the total number of children screened."
